  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong and global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This practice is illegal in virtually every country around the world.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Legal Frameworks**: Most countries have established comprehensive legal frameworks to combat money laundering. For example:\n   - In the United States, the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act are key pieces of legislation targeting money laundering.\n   - In the European Union, the Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) set the standard for member states.\n   - The United Nations has also addressed money laundering through international conventions, such as the UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (Palermo Convention).\n\n2. **International Cooperation**: Organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) work to set international standards and promote effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures to combat money laundering.\n\n3. **Severe Penalties**: Money laundering is a serious criminal offense that can result in severe penalties, including substantial fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\n4. **Global Consensus**: The illegality of money laundering is recognized globally, as it is associated with various forms of criminal activities, including drug trafficking, terrorism financing, corruption, and fraud.\n\n### Conclusion:\nThere is no significant dissent on the illegality of money laundering; it is universally regarded as a criminal activity and is actively targeted by law enforcement and regulatory bodies worldwide.",
